            <h2>17.2 Volume of an Ellipsoid: the Disk Method</h2>
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody></table>
    </td>
  </tr>
</tbody></table>
<p>Calculate the volume generate by rotating the ellipse of equation <img s=
rc=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/equations/section02_eq01.gi=
f" width=3D"85" height=3D"46" align=3D"absmiddle">around=20
  the x-axis.</p>
<p><b>Introduction</b></p>
<p>The method of disks consists of slicing the figure in question&nbsp;into=
 disk shaped=20
  slices, computing the volume of each and summing, ie, integrating over th=
ese.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/comment02.html">Com=
ment</a></p>
<p><b>Rotate the ellipse</b></p>
<p>By rotating the ellipse around the x-axis, <sub>&nbsp;</sub>we generate =
a solid=20
  of revolution called an&nbsp;ellipsoid whose volume can be calculated&nbs=
p;using the disk=20
  method.</p>
<p><b>Disk method</b></p>
<p>We revolve around the x-axis a thin vertical strip of height y =3D f(x) =
and thickness=20
  dx.</p>
<p>This generates a disk of radius y and thickness dx whose volume is dV.</=
p>
<p align=3D"center"> <img src=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/=
equations/section02_eq02.gif" width=3D"188" height=3D"213" align=3D"absmidd=
le">=20
</p>
<p><b>Volume of the ellipsoid</b></p>
<p>We get the volume of the ellipsoid by filling it with a very large numbe=
r of=20
  very thin disks, that is by integrating dV from x =3D -2 to x =3D 2.</p>
<p align=3D"center">Volume of th&nbsp; ellipsoid =3D V =3D <img src=3D"http=
s://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/equations/section02_eq03.gif" width=
=3D"117" height=3D"56" align=3D"absmiddle">=20
</p>
<p align=3D"center"> <img src=3D"https://math.mit.edu/~djk/18_01/chapter17/=
equations/section02_eq04.gif" width=3D"256" height=3D"224" align=3D"absmidd=
le">=20
</p>

